@@cHISTORY@@W

The warrior tradition traces to the road warden companies of the Keeper Era —
professional escorts who protected charter caravans across the desert road
network. After the Ninth Meridian Catastrophe shattered the eastern road
system, surviving militias reorganized as the Reaver Confederates and later
mercenary brotherhoods, carrying forward a doctrine forged by figures like
Warden-Sergeant Caleph Dunmar, who held the Seven Shade Arches forty-three
days against the Ashbound siege with nothing but defensive ground and
discipline. The Ash-and-Iron Decades further hardened the tradition: as
Midgaard's civic order militarized in response to the Ashfall Monsoon and the
fall of Evermeet, warrior training was systematized through requisition offices
and reserve depots. Modern warriors carry this layered inheritance — part road
guardian, part civic soldier, part mercenary craftsman of force.

@@cWARRIOR@@W

Warriors are masters of direct force: relentless front-line fighters trained to
break defenses, absorb pressure, and end conflicts in steel and momentum.

